Section 4.3 - Slope
Point-Slope Formula
The point-slope formula is a really useful way of calculating the
equation of a straight line.
Use the Formula to Find the Equation of a Straight Line
f you know the slope of the line and a point on the line, you can use the
point-slope formula to find the equation of the line.
The point-slope formula for finding the equation of a line is:
-
y − y₁ = m(x − x₁)
You substitute the x-coordinate of a point on the line for x₁ and the
y-coordinate of the same point for y₁. Watch out though -x and y are
variables and they stay as letters in the equation of the line.
Example 1
Find the equation of the line through (-4, 6) that has a slope of -3.
Solution
(x₁, y₁)=(-4, 6) and m = -3
y-y₁ = m(x-x₁)
⇒y-6=-3[x-(-4)]
⇒y-6=-3(x+4)
⇒y-6=-3x - 12
⇒ y + 3x = -6
